          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-3">Use this approach for <strong>any</strong> IM exam scenario:</p>
          <ol class="ml-5 list-decimal text-sm leading-relaxed text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 space-y-3">
            <li><strong>First read (2&nbsp;min):</strong> Skim the entire scenario. Don&rsquo;t annotate. Just absorb the big picture: What company? What problem? What technology? What&rsquo;s the plan?</li>
            <li><strong>Second read &mdash; annotate (5&nbsp;min):</strong> Go sentence by sentence. For each detail, write the course concept it triggers in the margin (e.g.&nbsp;&ldquo;Gartner&rdquo;, &ldquo;Porter&rdquo;, &ldquo;VRIN&rdquo;, &ldquo;selection bias&rdquo;). Every detail is there for a reason.</li>
            <li><strong>Flag the traps:</strong> Circle anything that feels &ldquo;too good to be true&rdquo; (inflated statistics), &ldquo;suspiciously specific&rdquo; (named technology standards &rarr; Earl&rsquo;s IT Strategy), or &ldquo;ethically questionable&rdquo; (hidden data tracking &rarr; GDPR).</li>
            <li><strong>Before answering each question:</strong> Re-read the question, go back to the scenario, find the exact sentence(s) that support your answer, and quote/reference them in your response.</li>
          </ol>
