              <li>[ ] Defining a Business Strategy</li>
              <li>[ ] Keeping information stakeholders happy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> This is all-or-nothing &mdash; you only get the point if every cross is correct. Think carefully about what the CIO role actually covers (Ch1). The CIO defines <em>IT strategy</em>, not business strategy.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--sky">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>
            <p><strong>Correct:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>&check; Watching new technologies</strong> &mdash; The CIO is responsible for observing and evaluating technological developments (one of the 4 ICT responsibilities).</li>
              <li><strong>&check; Keeping information stakeholders happy</strong> &mdash; The CIO manages information as a resource and serves the needs of information stakeholders at all levels (strategic, tactical, operational).</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Incorrect:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>&cross; Lawn Maintenance</strong> &mdash; Completely irrelevant to information management.</li>
              <li><strong>&cross; Defining a Business Strategy</strong> &mdash; The CIO defines the <em>IT strategy</em>, not the business strategy. Business strategy is set by the CEO/board. The CIO aligns IT strategy with business strategy (Earl's model: IS Strategy = What, IT Strategy = How, IM Strategy = Who/Where).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

