      <!-- TASK 2 — Terminology (6pts)                                  -->
      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <section id="task2" class="scroll-mt-24">
        <div class="task-heading task-heading--amber">
          <span class="task-badge task-badge--amber">Task 2</span>
          <h2>Terminology</h2>
          <span class="task-points">6 points</span>
        </div>

        <!-- 2a -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 2a (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Explain the terms Symbols, Data, Information, and Knowledge in one sentence each. Give an example for each term from the scenario.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> You need 8 things: 4 definitions + 4 scenario examples. Structure your answer as a clear list. Each definition should reference the hierarchy transition (syntax, semantics, pragmatics). Make the examples concrete and from the scenario &mdash; not generic.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--amber">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <div class="term-block">
              <h4>Symbols</h4>
              <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Symbols are the smallest representable unit &mdash; raw characters, digits, or signs that carry no meaning on their own.</p>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> The individual letters and digits like "M", "i", "S", "e", "9", "5" as they appear on a sensor readout before any interpretation.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="term-block">
              <h4>Data</h4>
              <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Data is created when symbols are arranged according to syntactic rules (grammar), giving them structure but not yet context-dependent meaning.</p>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> "MiSe sensor detected 95% load" &mdash; this is a structured string of symbols following syntax, but without knowing which screw or where, it's just data.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="term-block">
              <h4>Information</h4>
              <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Information arises when data is enriched with context (semantics) &mdash; the who, what, when, where that gives data meaning for a specific situation.</p>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> "Screw #4712 in Building A, Floor 3, has reached 95% load capacity at 14:30 today" &mdash; now the data has context and is actionable.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="term-block">
              <h4>Knowledge</h4>
              <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Knowledge is networked information combined with experience and judgment that enables a person to take purposeful action (pragmatics).</p>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> The maintenance engineer knows from experience that 95% load on wood screws in that building type means replacement is needed within 48 hours, and initiates the replacement order.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 2b -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 2b (3 pts)</span>
            <p>"90% of customers would pay up to 100 times the original price for a better screw." Which relevant context information was left out when transforming this information? How does it change your interpretation of the data?</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> This tests the five context questions (Who? What? When? Where? How?) and the concept that information quality depends on context. Identify the <em>selection bias</em> in the sample and explain how it inflates the statistic.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--amber">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>Missing context (the key issue is selection bias):</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Who was asked?</strong> Only companies that <em>already suffered from costly downtime and repairs</em>. This is a pre-filtered sample of those who experienced the most pain &mdash; not all customers.</li>
              <li><strong>What was the total population?</strong> We don't know how many total customers exist, or what percentage of all customers actually experienced costly downtime.</li>
              <li><strong>How was willingness measured?</strong> Stated willingness to pay ("would pay") is very different from actual purchasing behavior. People often overstate willingness in surveys.</li>
              <li><strong>When and where?</strong> Was this during/right after a failure event (emotional response) or in normal operations?</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>How this changes interpretation:</strong></p>
            <p>The 90% figure is misleadingly high because the sample is pre-filtered to those who already experienced the worst outcomes. If only 5% of all customers ever experience costly downtime, then the actual market willing to pay 100x is roughly 90% &times; 5% = 4.5% of the total customer base &mdash; a dramatically different business case. The statistic creates a false impression of massive demand when the real addressable market may be much smaller.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

