      <!-- TASK 3 — IT & IS Management (12pts)                          -->
      <!-- ============================================================ -->
      <section id="task3" class="scroll-mt-24">
        <div class="task-heading task-heading--emerald">
          <span class="task-badge task-badge--emerald">Task 3</span>
          <h2>Management of IT and IS</h2>
          <span class="task-points">12 points</span>
        </div>

        <!-- 3a -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 3a (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Describe your company's assessment regarding the choice of MiSe. Apply the terminology of the Gartner Hype Cycle.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Name the specific phase, justify it with evidence from the scenario, and explain what that phase means. Don't just say "Innovation Trigger" &mdash; prove it.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--emerald">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>
            <p>MiSe is currently at the <strong>Innovation Trigger</strong> phase of the Gartner Hype Cycle. Evidence:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>It was just published as a <strong>research paper</strong> by an American researcher &mdash; this is the earliest possible stage of a technology.</li>
              <li>It has received <strong>"very little attention yet"</strong> &mdash; the broader market is not yet aware of or excited about it.</li>
              <li>It is <strong>first-generation technology</strong> &mdash; no proven commercial implementations exist, requiring high customization and development effort.</li>
              <li>The company would need to work closely with engineers to <strong>design and test</strong> the sensors from scratch.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>By investing at this stage, the company is acting as a <strong>technology leader</strong> (as opposed to a follower), taking on high risk but potentially gaining first-mover advantage if MiSe proves viable.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 3b -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 3b (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Describe possible outcomes of this choice over time (again applying the Gartner Hype Cycle model and terminology).</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Walk through the remaining phases in order. For each, describe what could happen to MiSe specifically. Show you understand the full cycle, not just one phase.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--emerald">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>
            <p>After the Innovation Trigger, MiSe could progress through the following phases:</p>

            <ol>
              <li>
                <strong>Peak of Inflated Expectations:</strong> If the concept of "smart screws" gains media attention or industry hype, expectations could soar. Companies might overestimate what MiSe can deliver, leading to inflated demand projections (similar to the misleading 90% statistic).
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Trough of Disillusionment:</strong> Early implementations may reveal problems &mdash; sensor reliability in harsh environments, battery life limitations, false positives, or high manufacturing costs. Some early adopters may abandon the technology, and interest could plummet.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Slope of Enlightenment:</strong> With continued R&D, the company identifies which use cases truly work (e.g., aerospace and defense where safety justifies premium pricing). Second and third generation products improve reliability and reduce cost.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Plateau of Productivity:</strong> MiSe becomes a proven, mainstream technology. The company has established market leadership with patents protecting their IP. The technology delivers consistent, measurable value.
              </li>
            </ol>

            <p><strong>Key risk:</strong> Investing at the Innovation Trigger means high uncertainty. The technology might never reach the Plateau &mdash; it could stall in the Trough if fundamental technical barriers cannot be overcome (e.g., sensor miniaturization limits, cost of integration).</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 3c -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 3c (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Write a short assessment of the company's decision. Apply Strategies after Porter to support your argument.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Reference Porter's Generic Strategies matrix explicitly. Identify which strategy the company pursues, justify it, and optionally mention Porter's Five Forces to strengthen your argument. Don't forget the ethical issue with the hidden tracking feature.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--emerald">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>Porter's Generic Strategy applied:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>The company pursues <strong>Product Differentiation</strong> &mdash; sensor-enabled screws are a unique product offering that no competitor currently has. The company competes on <em>singularity</em> (uniqueness), not cost.</li>
              <li>Additionally, they target a <strong>Focus/Niche strategy</strong> &mdash; the product is aimed at industries where safety is critical and premium pricing is justified (aerospace, defense, high-risk construction).</li>
              <li>This is a <strong>Differentiation Focus</strong> strategy (top-left in Porter's matrix): unique product aimed at a specific market segment.</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Assessment using Porter's Five Forces:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Threat of substitutes:</strong> Reduced &mdash; sensor screws are hard to replicate, especially with patent protection.</li>
              <li><strong>Barriers to entry:</strong> Increased &mdash; patents + first-mover advantage + specialized engineering knowledge.</li>
              <li><strong>Bargaining power of customers:</strong> The 100x price premium is acceptable to customers in high-risk industries where failure costs far exceed screw costs.</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Critical concern:</strong> The plan to include a <strong>hidden tracking feature</strong> is a significant ethical and legal risk. Under GDPR and similar regulations, hidden data collection without informed consent is illegal. This could lead to lawsuits, fines, and reputational damage that would undermine the trust-based competitive advantage the company is building.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 3d -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 3d (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Now you are in charge for executing the project. Briefly summarize how you manage the project.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Distinguish between Project vs. Service (Ch3), choose an appropriate methodology (Agile vs. Waterfall), and justify your choice based on project characteristics. Mention the transition to service operations after delivery.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--emerald">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>1. This is a Project</strong> (not a service): It has a defined goal (develop sensor-enabled screws), a defined time span ("a few months"), and a unique deliverable. After initial delivery, it transitions to a service for ongoing monitoring and maintenance.</p>

            <p><strong>2. Methodology: Agile/Scrum</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Why Agile?</strong> This is a novel technology with high uncertainty. Requirements will evolve as the team learns what works with MiSe integration. A waterfall approach would be too rigid.</li>
              <li><strong>Short sprints</strong> (2-week cycles) to iteratively develop and test: first the sensor hardware integration, then the communication layer (Bluetooth), then the alerting system, then the configuration interface.</li>
              <li><strong>Frequent feedback loops</strong> with engineers and potential customers to validate assumptions early.</li>
              <li><strong>Scrum roles:</strong> Product Owner (from management, defining priorities), Scrum Master (facilitating the process), Development Team (engineers + developers).</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>3. Consider DevOps</strong> for the software component (sensor firmware, data processing backend, alerting service) &mdash; continuous integration and deployment enables rapid iteration.</p>

            <p><strong>4. Transition to Service:</strong> After the initial product launch, ongoing sensor monitoring, firmware updates, and customer support become a <em>service</em> operation (ITIL-based), no longer a project.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
