            <span class="question-label">Question 1 — Extra B</span>
            <p>The screw company decides: <em>"We will use Bluetooth Low Energy as the wireless standard for all sensor communication."</em> According to Earl's three strategy types, this statement belongs to:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>[ ] IS Strategy</li>
              <li>[ ] IT Strategy</li>
              <li>[ ] IM Strategy</li>
              <li>[ ] Business Strategy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Earl's model: IS = <em>What</em> (business applications), IT = <em>How</em> (technology architecture, standards), IM = <em>Who/Where</em> (structures and roles). A decision about a specific technology standard is a <em>How</em> question.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--sky">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>
            <p><strong>Correct:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>&check; IT Strategy</strong> &mdash; Choosing a specific wireless technology standard (BLE) is a <em>How</em> decision — it defines the technical architecture and communication protocol. This falls under IT Strategy in Earl's model.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Incorrect:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>&cross; IS Strategy</strong> &mdash; IS Strategy answers <em>What</em> — which business applications to build. "Build a sensor monitoring system" would be an IS Strategy decision. The choice of BLE as a protocol is not about <em>what</em> to build, but <em>how</em> to build it.</li>
              <li><strong>&cross; IM Strategy</strong> &mdash; IM Strategy answers <em>Who/Where</em> — organizational structures, roles, responsibilities. "The engineering team manages sensor firmware" would be IM Strategy.</li>
              <li><strong>&cross; Business Strategy</strong> &mdash; Business Strategy is set by the CEO/board and covers overall competitive positioning. It is not part of Earl's IT-specific model.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

