        <!-- 2c: Information Quality -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 2c (3 pts)</span>
            <p>The screw company collected the following sensor test data during a pilot:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc ml-4">
              <li>Some screws report load as a percentage (e.g., "85%"), others as raw voltage (e.g., "2.4V"), with no conversion table provided.</li>
              <li>Three out of twenty test screws never transmitted any data during the pilot.</li>
              <li>Sensor readings are only synced once per day, but the scenario requires real-time alerting.</li>
              <li>Reports are generated as raw CSV files with no column headers.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Identify which <strong>information quality dimensions</strong> are violated by each issue.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> The four quality categories are Intrinsic, Contextual, Presentational, and Access. Match each data flaw to a specific dimension. Name the category <em>and</em> the specific sub-dimension (e.g., "Presentational — Uniformity"). One issue can violate multiple dimensions.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--amber">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <table class="model-table" style="border-color: var(--tw-border-opacity, 1);">
              <thead class="!bg-amber-100 dark:!bg-amber-900/40">
                <tr>
                  <th class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700 !text-amber-900 dark:!text-amber-100">Issue</th>
                  <th class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700 !text-amber-900 dark:!text-amber-100">Violated Dimension(s)</th>
                  <th class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700 !text-amber-900 dark:!text-amber-100">Explanation</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700"><strong>Mixed units (% vs V)</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">Presentational &mdash; <strong>Uniformity</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">Data uses inconsistent formats/units, making comparison impossible without a conversion standard.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700"><strong>3 of 20 screws missing</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">Contextual &mdash; <strong>Completeness</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">15% of sensors provided no data at all. The dataset is incomplete &mdash; decisions based on it ignore those screws entirely.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700"><strong>Once-daily sync</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">Contextual &mdash; <strong>Currentness</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">Data is up to 24 hours stale. For a system that promises real-time alerting, this violates timeliness requirements entirely.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700"><strong>Raw CSV, no headers</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">Presentational &mdash; <strong>Understandability</strong>, <strong>Clarity</strong></td>
                  <td class="!border-amber-200 dark:!border-amber-700">Without column headers, a reader cannot determine what each column represents. The information is technically present but practically unusable without external documentation.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <p><strong>Key takeaway:</strong> Even if sensor data is <em>correct</em> (Intrinsic quality is fine), it can still be useless if it fails on Contextual (completeness, timeliness) or Presentational (uniformity, clarity) dimensions. Information quality must be evaluated across <em>all four categories</em>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- 2d: Picot's Three Dimensions -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 2d (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Apply <strong>Picot's three dimensions of information demand</strong> to the MiSe project. For each dimension, give a concrete example from the scenario. Then identify at least two <strong>gaps</strong> between the dimensions.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Picot's model has three overlapping circles: Objective need (what the task requires), Subjective need (what people think they need), and Available information (what actually exists). The gaps between them reveal training gaps, noise, and information gaps. Draw the Venn diagram mentally and fill each region.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--amber">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>The three dimensions applied to MiSe:</strong></p>

            <div class="term-block">
              <h4>Objective Need (task-derived)</h4>
              <p>The MiSe project objectively requires: real-time load data per screw, failure threshold parameters, screw location mapping, maintenance crew contact routing, and regulatory compliance data (especially regarding the hidden tracking feature and GDPR).</p>
            </div>

            <div class="term-block">
              <h4>Subjective Need (person-derived)</h4>
              <p>Management <em>thinks</em> they need: the "90% willingness to pay 100x" market statistic (which is biased), customer usage tracking data (the hidden feature), and broad market demand projections. Engineers think they need: detailed MiSe research papers and technical specs for sensor integration.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="term-block">
              <h4>Available Information</h4>
              <p>What actually exists: the original MiSe research paper (which received "very little attention"), the company's existing customer database, the biased survey of customers who experienced downtime, and existing screw specification data.</p>
            </div>

            <p><strong>Identified gaps:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Information Gap (Objective + Subjective, but NOT Available):</strong> Real-time sensor reliability data for production environments does not exist yet &mdash; MiSe is at the Innovation Trigger stage. The project needs this data but it must be generated through R&amp;D and testing.</li>
              <li><strong>Training Gap (Objective, but NOT Subjective):</strong> Management does not realize they need GDPR compliance analysis for the hidden tracking feature. This is objectively required but the scenario shows no awareness of it.</li>
              <li><strong>Noise (Subjective, but NOT Objective):</strong> The "90% would pay 100x" statistic feels important to management but is based on a biased sample and is not objectively useful for planning without correcting for selection bias.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

