        <!-- 4f: DevOps vs DevSecOps -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question 4f (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Describe the <strong>DevOps</strong> pipeline for the MiSe software platform (sensor firmware, data backend, alerting service). Then explain how <strong>DevSecOps</strong> extends it &mdash; where does security fit into each phase?</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> First describe the standard DevOps loop (Plan &rarr; Build &rarr; Test &rarr; Deploy &rarr; Operate &rarr; Monitor). Then overlay the DevSecOps security activities at each phase. Use the MiSe scenario to make it concrete.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--purple">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>DevOps pipeline for the MiSe platform:</strong></p>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Plan:</strong> Define sprint goals (e.g., "implement Bluetooth data ingestion"). Product Owner prioritizes backlog. Knowledge sharing between hardware and software teams.</li>
              <li><strong>Build:</strong> Developers write sensor firmware, data backend, and alerting service code. Git-based SCM with CI &mdash; every commit triggers automated builds.</li>
              <li><strong>Test:</strong> Automated unit, integration (sensor-to-backend), and E2E tests (simulate overload &rarr; verify alert). Critical given the safety-critical nature.</li>
              <li><strong>Deploy:</strong> Infrastructure as Code for cloud backend (PaaS). Containerized services via CI/CD. Sensor firmware via OTA updates.</li>
              <li><strong>Operate:</strong> "You built it, you run it" &mdash; dev team monitors production. Cloud provider handles infrastructure.</li>
              <li><strong>Monitor:</strong> Runtime monitoring of sensor streams, alert delivery rates, system health. Continuous feedback loop back to Plan.</li>
            </ol>

            <p><strong>DevSecOps extension &mdash; security at each phase:</strong></p>
            <table class="model-table">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Security Activity</th><th>MiSe-Specific Example</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Develop</strong></td>
                  <td>Requirements analysis, secure coding</td>
                  <td>Identify hidden tracking as a privacy risk. Secure Bluetooth communication against eavesdropping.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Build</strong></td>
                  <td>SAST (Static Application Security Testing)</td>
                  <td>Scan firmware/backend for buffer overflows, SQL injection in data storage.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Test</strong></td>
                  <td>White box DAST, Black box DAST</td>
                  <td>Pen-test the alerting API. Test for sensor data spoofing/tampering.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Release</strong></td>
                  <td>Digital signing</td>
                  <td>Sign firmware updates to prevent malicious injection into deployed sensors.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Deploy</strong></td>
                  <td>Security configuration, scanning</td>
                  <td>Least-privilege cloud access. Scan container images for vulnerabilities.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Operate</strong></td>
                  <td>Security patching</td>
                  <td>Regular backend patching. OTA security patches for sensor firmware.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Monitor</strong></td>
                  <td>Security monitoring, auditing</td>
                  <td>Detect anomalous sensor behavior (tampering). Audit customer data access logs.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <p><strong>Key principle:</strong> DevSecOps <strong>shifts security left</strong> &mdash; security starts at requirements/coding, not as a final gate. Critical for MiSe because: (1) sensor data is safety-critical, and (2) the hidden tracking feature raises GDPR concerns that should be caught during requirements, not after deployment.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

