            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <table class="model-table">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Property</th><th>Meaning</th><th>MiSe Example</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Mapping</strong></td>
                  <td>A model represents something in the real world.</td>
                  <td>The UML Class Diagram of the monitoring system <em>represents</em> real-world entities: physical screws, sensors, maintenance crews, and their relationships.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Reduction</strong></td>
                  <td>A model leaves out irrelevant details.</td>
                  <td>The class diagram does not model the screw's physical dimensions, weight, or material composition &mdash; only the attributes relevant to monitoring (screwID, location, load capacity). Irrelevant details are <em>reduced away</em>.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Pragmatics</strong></td>
                  <td>A model serves a specific purpose.</td>
                  <td>The Use Case diagram serves the <em>purpose</em> of communicating system scope and actor interactions to stakeholders. The Class Diagram serves a different purpose: guiding developers on data structure. Same system, different models, different purposes.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Models vs. Diagrams -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question — Models vs. Diagrams (1 pt)</span>
            <p>Explain the difference between a <strong>model</strong> and a <strong>diagram</strong>. Can a model element exist that is not shown in any diagram? Can one model element appear in multiple diagrams?</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> This tests whether you understand that diagrams are <em>views</em> of a model, not the model itself. The model is the single source of truth. Three key facts: (1) one element &rarr; many diagrams, (2) an element not in any diagram still exists in the model, (3) you can have a model with zero diagrams.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--purple">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>Model:</strong> A (system) model contains <strong>all</strong> system elements and their relations. It is the complete, authoritative representation of the system &mdash; structured as a hierarchical tree. The model is the <strong>single source of truth</strong>.</p>

            <p><strong>Diagram:</strong> A diagram visualizes a <strong>selection</strong> of elements and relations from the model. It is a graphical <em>view</em> of part of the model, not the model itself.</p>

            <p><strong>Key distinctions:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Yes</strong> &mdash; a model element can exist that is not shown in any diagram. It is still part of the model.</li>
              <li><strong>Yes</strong> &mdash; one model element can appear in multiple diagrams. For example, the <code>Sensor</code> class appears in both the Class Diagram and the Use Case Diagram (as an actor).</li>
              <li>You can create a model <strong>without any diagrams at all</strong> &mdash; the model is the source of truth, diagrams are just views.</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>MiSe example:</strong> The "Alert" class exists once in the system model. It appears in the Class Diagram (showing attributes and associations), the Use Case Diagram (related to "Send stress alert"), and the Activity Diagram (as the output of "Generate replacement report"). Three diagrams, one model element.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Domain vs. System Model / Conceptual vs. Specification -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question — Modeling Dimensions (3 pts)</span>
            <p>Explain the two orthogonal dimensions of modeling: <strong>Modeling Object</strong> (Domain vs. System Model) and <strong>Modeling Purpose</strong> (Conceptual vs. Specification Model). For each of the four combinations, give an example from the MiSe project.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Draw a 2&times;2 matrix mentally. Rows: Domain Model vs. System Model. Columns: Conceptual vs. Specification. Fill each cell with an example. Domain = real-world concepts only. System = includes implementation concepts. Conceptual = for understanding. Specification = formally precise (code-generatable).
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--purple">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>Dimension 1 &mdash; Modeling Object (what is modeled?):</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Domain Model:</strong> Contains only real-world concepts from the application domain. No implementation details. Example: Screw, Sensor, MaintenanceCrew, Alert &mdash; concepts that exist in the physical world independent of any software system.</li>
              <li><strong>System Model:</strong> Extends the domain model with implementation concepts. Example: Same classes <em>plus</em> DatabaseConnector, BluetoothAdapter, NotificationService, APIGateway &mdash; these exist only because we are building a software system.</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Dimension 2 &mdash; Modeling Purpose (what is it modeled for?):</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Conceptual Model:</strong> Prioritizes <em>shared understanding</em> over formal precision. Like a whiteboard sketch. Used for communication between stakeholders who may not know UML syntax.</li>
              <li><strong>Specification Model:</strong> Formally precise &mdash; includes full types, constraints, multiplicities. Can be used to generate code or test cases.</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>The 2&times;2 matrix applied to MiSe:</strong></p>
            <table class="model-table">
              <thead>
                <tr><th></th><th>Conceptual (understanding)</th><th>Specification (precision)</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Domain Model</strong></td>
                  <td>A whiteboard sketch showing Screw &rarr; Sensor &rarr; Alert &rarr; MaintenanceCrew with plain arrows. Used in a kickoff meeting with management to align on what the system monitors.</td>
                  <td>A formal UML domain class diagram with typed attributes (<code>loadPercentage: float</code>), exact multiplicities (<code>1..*</code>), and OCL constraints. Used by analysts to validate business rules.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>System Model</strong></td>
                  <td>An architecture overview diagram showing "Cloud Backend", "Bluetooth Layer", "Alert Service" as boxes with arrows. Used to explain the system to new team members.</td>
                  <td>A complete UML system class diagram with DatabaseConnector, BluetoothAdapter, full method signatures, visibility modifiers, and package structure. Used to generate code scaffolding.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Generalization / Inheritance -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question — Generalization &amp; Inheritance (3 pts)</span>
            <p>The MiSe monitoring system has different types of alerts: <strong>WarningAlert</strong> (screw approaching threshold), <strong>CriticalAlert</strong> (screw exceeding threshold), and <strong>SystemAlert</strong> (sensor malfunction). Model this using <strong>UML generalization</strong>. Explain attribute inheritance and association inheritance.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> Draw a supertype with shared attributes, then subtypes with specific attributes. Use the hollow triangle arrow notation (subtype &rarr; supertype). Remember: subtypes inherit ALL supertype attributes AND associations. An instance of a subtype IS an instance of the supertype.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--purple">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>Supertype:</strong></p>
            <div class="cockburn-uc">
              <div class="uc-field">
                <span class="uc-label">Alert (supertype)</span>
                <span>Attributes: alertID, timestamp, urgencyLevel, message, status</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="mt-3"><strong>Subtypes (each inherits all Alert attributes and adds its own):</strong></p>
            <div class="cockburn-uc">
              <div class="uc-field">
                <span class="uc-label">WarningAlert</span>
                <span>Additional attributes: currentLoadPercentage, timeToThreshold, recommendedAction</span>
              </div>
              <div class="uc-field">
                <span class="uc-label">CriticalAlert</span>
                <span>Additional attributes: exceedancePercentage, immediateActionRequired: boolean, escalationLevel</span>
              </div>
              <div class="uc-field">
                <span class="uc-label">SystemAlert</span>
                <span>Additional attributes: sensorErrorCode, lastKnownBatteryLevel, diagnosticData</span>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="mt-3"><strong>Attribute inheritance:</strong> Every WarningAlert, CriticalAlert, and SystemAlert automatically has alertID, timestamp, urgencyLevel, message, and status &mdash; these are inherited from the Alert supertype. A <code>CriticalAlert</code> instance <strong>IS</strong> an <code>Alert</code> instance.</p>

            <p><strong>Association inheritance:</strong> If <code>Alert</code> has an association to <code>MaintenanceCrew</code> (0..* &mdash; 1..1), then all three subtypes inherit this association. Every WarningAlert, CriticalAlert, and SystemAlert is assigned to a MaintenanceCrew. However, if only <code>CriticalAlert</code> has an association to <code>IncidentReport</code>, the other subtypes do <em>not</em> inherit it &mdash; subtype-specific associations apply only to that subtype.</p>

            <div class="diagram-placeholder">
              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 italic">In the actual exam, draw this as:</p>
              <ul class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1 space-y-0.5">
                <li>&bull; <code>Alert</code> class rectangle at the top with its attributes</li>
                <li>&bull; Three subtype rectangles below, each with only their <em>additional</em> attributes</li>
                <li>&bull; <strong>Hollow triangle arrows</strong> pointing from each subtype up to <code>Alert</code></li>
                <li>&bull; Associations from <code>Alert</code> to <code>MaintenanceCrew</code> (inherited by all subtypes)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Visibility -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question — Visibility / Access Operators (1 pt)</span>
            <p>In UML class diagrams, what do the following symbols mean before an attribute or operation? Match each symbol to its visibility level and explain who can access it.</p>
            <ul>
              <li><code>+</code></li>
              <li><code>-</code></li>
              <li><code>#</code></li>
              <li><code>~</code></li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> This is a pure recall question &mdash; memorize all four. The most commonly confused pair is <code>#</code> (protected &mdash; this class + subclasses) vs. <code>~</code> (package &mdash; only inside this package). Think: <code>#</code> = family (inheritance), <code>~</code> = neighbors (same package).
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--purple">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <table class="model-table">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>Symbol</th><th>Name</th><th>Accessible From</th><th>MiSe Example</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><code>+</code></td>
                  <td><strong>Public</strong></td>
                  <td>All classes with access to this package</td>
                  <td><code>+ getLoadPercentage(): float</code> &mdash; any class can call this to read a sensor's current load.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><code>-</code></td>
                  <td><strong>Private</strong></td>
                  <td>Only this class</td>
                  <td><code>- rawVoltage: float</code> &mdash; internal sensor calibration data; only the Sensor class itself can access this.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><code>#</code></td>
                  <td><strong>Protected</strong></td>
                  <td>This class and all subclasses</td>
                  <td><code># escalate(): void</code> on the Alert supertype &mdash; WarningAlert, CriticalAlert, and SystemAlert (subclasses) can all call it, but external classes cannot.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><code>~</code></td>
                  <td><strong>Package</strong></td>
                  <td>Only inside this package</td>
                  <td><code>~ validateThreshold(): boolean</code> on ThresholdConfig &mdash; accessible to other classes in the same <code>monitoring</code> package but not from the <code>notification</code> package.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <p><strong>Memory aid:</strong> From most open to most restricted: <code>+</code> (everyone) &rarr; <code>~</code> (package neighbors) &rarr; <code>#</code> (family/subclasses) &rarr; <code>-</code> (self only).</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- System Boundary & Context Boundary -->
        <div class="qa-block">
          <div class="question-box">
            <span class="question-label">Question — System &amp; Context Boundaries (3 pts)</span>
            <p>For the Smart Screw Monitoring System, define the <strong>system boundary</strong> and the <strong>context boundary</strong>. List what is <em>inside</em> the system, what is <em>outside the system but inside the context</em> (operational context), and what is <em>outside the context</em> entirely. Identify the five SuD properties.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="strategy-tip">
            <strong>Exam strategy:</strong> The SuD (System under Development) has five properties: operational context, context boundary, inner structure, interfaces, and behavior. The system boundary separates what you build from what interacts with it. The context boundary separates relevant external entities from irrelevant ones. Actors sit <em>between</em> the two boundaries.
          </div>

          <div class="answer-box answer-box--purple">
            <span class="answer-label">Model Answer</span>

            <p><strong>The five SuD properties applied to MiSe:</strong></p>

            <table class="model-table">
              <thead>
                <tr><th>SuD Property</th><th>MiSe Application</th></tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Operational context</strong></td>
                  <td>The environment influencing the system: Maintenance crews (humans), screw monitoring processes, sensor hardware, Bluetooth network, customer organizations, cloud infrastructure providers.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Context boundary</strong></td>
                  <td>Separates relevant from irrelevant. <em>Inside context:</em> maintenance crews, sensors, customers, cloud providers. <em>Outside context:</em> the screw manufacturing process, supply chain logistics, patent office, HR department.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Inner structure</strong></td>
                  <td>The system's internal components: data processing engine, alert generation module, threshold configuration module, notification dispatcher, data storage layer.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Interfaces</strong></td>
                  <td>Define the system boundary. <em>Input interfaces:</em> Bluetooth sensor data receiver, REST API for configuration. <em>Output interfaces:</em> SMS/email/push notification API, dashboard web interface, reporting API.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><strong>Behavior</strong></td>
                  <td>Observable at the interfaces: receives sensor readings, generates alerts when thresholds are exceeded, delivers notifications, provides real-time dashboard data.</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <p><strong>Boundary mapping:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Inside system boundary:</strong> Alert engine, data storage, threshold logic, notification dispatcher, dashboard backend &mdash; this is what we build.</li>
              <li><strong>Outside system, inside context:</strong> MiSe sensors (hardware actor), maintenance crews (human actor), administrators (human actor), cloud infrastructure (external service), Bluetooth network &mdash; these interact with the system through interfaces.</li>
              <li><strong>Outside context entirely:</strong> Screw manufacturing machinery, raw material suppliers, patent attorneys, company HR, lawn maintenance &mdash; irrelevant to the monitoring system.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

      </section>

    </main>

    <!-- ===== Theme init script ===== -->
    <script is:inline>
      const theme = localStorage.getItem('theme') ||
        (window.matchMedia('(prefers-color-scheme: dark)').matches ? 'dark' : 'light');
      document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark', theme === 'dark');
    </script>

    <!-- ===== Theme toggle script ===== -->
    <script>
      const themeToggle = document.getElementById('theme-toggle');
      themeToggle?.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const isDark = document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark');
        localStorage.setItem('theme', isDark ? 'dark' : 'light');
      });
    </script>
